<definition id="fs-idm4412224">
<term>carbonate</term>
<meaning id="fs-idm68673552">salt of the anion <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mtext>CO</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msub><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mo>2−</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo>;</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> often formed by the reaction of carbon dioxide with bases</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idm108042736">
<term>hydrogen carbonate</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp29769440">salt of carbonic acid, H<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> (containing the anion <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mtext>HCO</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msub><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>−</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> in which one hydrogen atom has been replaced; an acid carbonate; also known as <emphasis effect="italics">bicarbonate ion</emphasis></meaning>
</definition>
